text:
The Venetian truly is an exquisite hotel: gorgeous lobby, beautiful casino, tons of shopping, eateries galore (including a nice selection of fine dining), a dance club, fascinating exhibits, and incredible shows (we saw Tim McGraw and Faith Hill). The hotel is immaculate. Service is impeccable on every level from the front desk staff and concierge to the bellboy, housekeeping, and security. Check in and out are a breeze.

The rooms\/suites are elegantly appointed. Ultra comfortable beds with millions of pillows; 3 televisions (including one in the bath); marble and mirrors everywhere; gold fixtures; vanity table in the bath; remote-controlled shades and black-out drapes over huge windows.

So then why only 4 stars? It's pseudo luxury; when you see the suite you are blown away...until you realize there were a lot of little shortcuts taken and things not thought through that make staying at the Venetian irritating\/inconvenient. 
 - There are no fans at all in the bath or toilet areas; 
 - the lighting is very soft, making it difficult to apply makeup or to shave;
 - the entire area under the sinks is open and completely wasted because there is no shelf (or storage) for toiletries, cosmetic bags or styling tools, and only limited space on the counter; 
 - beautiful piece of furniture in the bedroom area is not a dresser, it does not have drawers, only (black) shelves so you have to live out of your suitcase;
 - there are wonderfully convenient light switches for the bedside lighting on the wall above your pillows, but there is no way to turn one lamp on so you can read and turn the other off so your spouse can sleep
 - the door is paper thin, not only can you clearly hear conversations out in the hallway, if you are in the hallway you can hear every word of the conversations people are having in their rooms...we were fortunate to at the very end of the hall so we did not have people walking past, only those with the room next to ours and across the hall. Personally, I would have sacrificed the electric drapes and installed thicker doors if it were a budget issue.
 - no coffee maker\/french press\/Keurig in the room. I have been informed that this is typical in Vegas, and while that may be true, it makes me grouchy trying to get myself presentable without my coffee fix to go down to get my coffee fix (which you cannot charge to your room).

I realize that those details are tiny, but they are so important (and so obvious when missing). It's those details that really distinguish the finer hotels. 

Overall, I felt glamorous (and quite pampered) while staying at the Venetian and I would consider staying again.
